This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of cs.CL (Computation and Language) as it deals with natural language processing (NLP) and specifically focuses on the generation of complex derived word forms. The use of neural sequence-to-sequence models also suggests a focus on machine learning and deep learning, which are common topics in the cs.CL sub-category. 

The paper may also belong to cs.LG (Machine Learning) as it applies neural models to the task of derivational paradigm completion. 

cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is another likely sub-category as the paper deals with the development of intelligent systems that can generate complex word forms. 

cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) is also a possible sub-category as the paper uses neural models to solve the task of derivational paradigm completion. 

Finally, cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is a less likely sub-category, but it is possible that the paper may involve the development of algorithms or data structures to support the neural models used in the task.
